  "query": "What is the effect of providing education programmes on forest conservation efforts in South America?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available action documents, there is limited evidence specifically about education programmes and forest conservation in South America. For forest education programmes specifically, no evidence was found for their effect on forests (Action 1158). However, there is some relevant evidence from South America regarding education and conservation programmes more broadly. One study from Venezuela found no evidence for decreases in yellow-shouldered parrot poaching following an educational programme in local schools, though the authors argued that benefits would likely be seen later in the project (Action 274). In terms of community-based forest management approaches (which often include educational components), one replicated, site comparison study in Colombia found that deforestation rates in community-managed forests did not differ from deforestation rates in forests that were not managed by local communities, or in uninhabited national parks (Action 1152). Related evidence from community engagement in conservation activities shows some positive results - a site comparison study in Brazil found that areas where community-based management of fishing practices was implemented had higher abundance of river turtles than areas with no community-based management (Action 3681).",
